# Outbound security (Gateway → True Engine)
The engine wraps `/api/v1/*` in an HMAC verifier + ReplayGuard (`internal/api/hmac.go`,
`replay.go`). **Every** outbound call MUST send all four headers or it is rejected:

| Header            | Value                                                              |
|-------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------|
| `X-Operator-Code` | our operator code, from `ENGINE_OPERATOR_CODE` (selects the secret)|
| `X-Signature`     | hex HMAC-SHA256 of the **raw request body** with `ENGINE_SECRET_KEY`|
| `X-Timestamp`     | current Unix **seconds** (engine rejects > 300s old / > 30s ahead) |
| `X-Nonce`         | a **fresh** UUID per physical attempt (single-use, engine-cached)  |

- Serialize the body **once**; sign and send those exact bytes.
- `X-Nonce` is fresh on every retry; the idempotency key (below) stays stable.
- There is **no** `X-Idempotency-Key` — the engine ignores it.

---

# Inbound security (Game Aggregator → Gateway)
B2B routes under `/api/webhooks/provider/*` are **webhook receivers** called by external
Game Aggregators (e.g. Pragmatic Play). **Players never call these and never authorize
their own winnings.** There is no player JWT on these routes. Instead verify the
provider, exactly like the engine verifies us:
1. Read the **raw** body (before JSON parse).
2. Constant-time compare `X-Signature` against HMAC-SHA256(rawBody, provider secret)
   selected by `X-Provider-Code` from `PROVIDER_WEBHOOK_SECRETS`.
3. Reject `X-Timestamp` older than 300s (and far-future).
4. Reject a reused `X-Nonce` (single-use cache) → replay protection.
Only after all four pass do you translate the payload and call the engine.

